        }
      }, "In 1828, General Darling reported that the Chippewas who formerly occupied the lands about Lake Simcoe, Holland River and the unsettled country expressed their desire to become Christians and adopt the habits of civilized life, so in 1830 Lieutenant-Governor Sir J. Colborne, assigned them attract of 9800 acres of land on the northwest shore of Lake Simcoe.  There were three tribes of Chippewas under Chiefs Yellow Head, Aisance and Snake, also some Pottawatamies from Drummond Island.  A descendant of Chief Aisance, bearing the same name, is among our Indians."), /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("p", {
