        }
      }, "The early camp was for a period of one week, which by stages has been lengthened to seven.  The cost of living at the first camp was $9.00.  In 1890 the assessment was fixed at $30.00, which, after paying $14.35 for the railroad fare and $1.50 each way for the Pullman, left $12.65 for living expenses for the two weeks in camp.  And they flourished on it.  The charge for \u201Crowers\u201D, (they scorned \u201Cguides\u201D in those days) was 50\xA2 a day.  It was not until 1902 that they jumped the rate on \u201Cguides\u201D to 25\xA2 a meal.  And the daily wage of the slavey was $1.50."), /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("p", {
